        <m>{\large \textbf{15.1 Markov Chains}}</m>
        <p>1. Recall the definition of a regular stochastic matrix.</p>
        <m></m><p></p>
        <p><m>{\mathbf{Definition}}</m>:</p>
        <p>A stochastic matrix <m>P</m> is <m>\textbf{regular}</m> if there is some <m>k</m> such that every entry of <m>P^k</m> is <m>\framebox{________}.</m></p>

        <m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p>
        <p>Determine whether <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> are a regular stochastic matrices.</p>
        <me>P = \begin{pmatrix} .8 \amp 0 \\ .2 \amp 1 \end{pmatrix}, \textup{ }Q = \frac{1}{4}\begin{pmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 2 \\ 3 \amp 1 \amp 2 \end{pmatrix}</me>
    </page>
    <page>
        <p>2. We use the idea of a regular stochastic matrix to describe convergence of Markov chains.</p>
         <p><m>{\mathbf{Theorem}}</m>:</p>
         <p>If <m>P</m> is a regular stochastic matrix, then <m>\vec{x}_{k+1} = P\vec{x}_k</m> converges to a <m>\framebox{____________________}</m> steady-state vector <m>\vec{q}</m> as <m>k \rightarrow \infty</m>.</p>
         <m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p>
         <p>Suppose there are two cities, X and Y. Every year,</p>
         <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    70% of the people from X stay in X, the remaining 30% move to Y.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    40% of the people from Y stay in Y, the remaining 60% move to X.
                </p>
            </li>
         </ul>
         <p>The initial populations of X and Y are <m>100</m> and <m>200</m>, respectively.</p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        What is the stochastic matrix that represents this situation?
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        After a long period of time, what is the population in city X?
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
    </page>
    <page>
        <m>{\large \textbf{15.2 Eigenvalue Problems}}</m>
        <p>1. The Markov Chains we were exploring have a connection to the eigenvalue problem.</p>
        <m></m><p></p>
        <p><m>{\mathbf{Definition}}</m>:</p>
        <p>If <m>A</m> is real <m>n \times n</m>, and there is a <m>\vec{v} \neq \vec{0}</m> in <m>\mathbb{C}^n</m>, and</p>
        <me>A\vec{v} = \framebox{___________}</me> 
        <p>then <m>\vec{v}</m> is an <m>\textbf{eigenvector}</m> for <m>A</m>, and <m>\lambda \in \mathbb{C}</m> is the corresponding <m>\textbf{eigenvalue}</m>.</p>
<m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p>
        <p>(a) Is <m>\lambda = 2</m> an eigenvalue of <m>A</m>? Do not compute the characteristic polynomial.</p>
        <me>A = \begin{pmatrix} 3 \amp 2 \\ 3 \amp 8 \end{pmatrix}</me>
        <m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p>

        <p>(b) Determine whether <m>\vec{v}_1</m> and <m>\vec{v}_2</m> are eigenvectors of <m>A</m>. If so, what are their eigenvalues? Do not use the characteristic polynomial.</p>
        <me>A = \begin{pmatrix} -3 \amp -3 \amp 2 \\ 6 \amp 4 \amp 0 \\ 5 \amp 3 \amp 0 \end{pmatrix}, 
            \textup{ } \vec{v}_1 = \begin{pmatrix} -1 \\ 1 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}, \textup{ } \vec{v}_2 = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}
        </me>
        <m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p>
    </page>
    <page>
